		<li class="comment byuser comment-author-rolfje bypostauthor odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 highlander-comment" id="comment-484">
				<div id="div-comment-484" class="comment-body">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
						<cite class="fn"><a href='http://www.rolfje.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>rolfje</a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>		</div>
		
		<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://rolfje.wordpress.com/2008/01/26/philips-wake-up-light-review/#comment-484">
			Friday 2008-10-10 at 19:14 \19\Oct\UTC +0000</a>		</div>

		<p>Personally I hope that Philips never, ever introduces LED lights in the wakeup light. The reason is kind of explained in my post in the section on Neodymium bulbs. Current LED lights can not approximate daylight because they emit narrow bands of single colors, like fluorescent light. Although for most people this will be ok, it will not be as good as a normal &#8220;glowing wolfram wire&#8221; lamp which emits a completer spectrum. Explanations on LED&#8217;s and their spectrum can be found here:<br />
<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Light-emitting_diode" rel="nofollow">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Light-emitting_diode</a></p>
<p>White LED&#8217;s also introduce the possibility of a &#8220;blue light hazard&#8221;, because the blue light component is used to make a LED look &#8220;white&#8221;. More info on Blue light hazrd info is here:<br />
<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blue-light_hazard" rel="nofollow">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blue-light_hazard</a></p>
<p>The light is only on for 30 to 45 minutes each morning. Energy saving in that lightbulb is senseless and the expenses likely do not outweigh the savings. If all you have is a hammer&#8230;</p>

		<div class="reply">
			<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2008/01/26/philips-wake-up-light-review/?replytocom=484#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("div-comment-484", "484", "respond", "198")'>Reply</a>		</div>
